## Poverty drives food insecurity {.scale-slide}

::: {.r-stretch}
![](figures/08_poverty_gradient.png){fig-align="center"}
:::

::: {.notes}
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 2: Poverty Gradient

If you remember one statistic from this presentation, remember this: when
a family's income rises above 185% of the federal poverty line — the same
threshold the federal government already uses for WIC eligibility and
reduced-price school meals — food insecurity drops 5×.

39.4% of households below the poverty line are food insecure. Above 185%
of poverty, only 7.9% are.

This is not a coincidence. The federal nutrition assistance programs were
designed to cover precisely the populations where food insecurity is
concentrated — and they do. The question for Congress is not whether
nutrition assistance works. It does. The question is whether to fund it
at the level the data demands.

Source: USDA ERR-358, 2024.
:::


## Food insecurity is a story of who, not just how many {.scale-slide}

::: {.r-stretch}
![](figures/09_who_is_affected.png){fig-align="center"}
:::

::: {.notes}
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 3: Who is Affected

The national rate hides a story.

1 in 3 female-headed households in America are food insecure — 36.8%.
Black households: 24.4%. Hispanic households: 20.2%. Households with
children: 18.4%. The U.S. average is 13.7%, shown by the dashed line.

Food insecurity is not evenly distributed. It is concentrated in the
households that are also most economically vulnerable: single mothers,
households of color, and families with children.

This matters for policy design. A program that targets the average will
miss the populations who need it most. Programs designed around these
disparities — like school meals, WIC, and SNAP for families with kids —
are the ones that move these numbers.

Source: USDA ERR-358, 2024.
:::


## The pandemic-era safety net worked. Then it expired. {.scale-slide}

::: {.r-stretch}
![](figures/02_trend_reversal.png){fig-align="center"}
:::

::: {.notes}
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 4: The Trend Reversal

This is the most important policy slide in the deck.

Look at 2021. We were in the middle of a global pandemic. Food insecurity
should have spiked. Instead, it dropped to 10.2% — the lowest rate ever
recorded in the United States since USDA began tracking this in 1995.

That wasn't an accident. Congress had passed the expanded Child Tax
Credit, SNAP emergency allotments, P-EBT for kids when schools closed,
and three rounds of stimulus. The Child Tax Credit alone sent monthly
checks to families with children for the second half of 2021.

When those programs expired — the CTC expanded version ended December 2021,
SNAP emergency allotments fully ended in March 2023 — food insecurity
climbed 3.5 percentage points. That's roughly 13 million additional people
who became food insecure in just three years.

We have proof of what works. We just stopped doing it. The remaining
slides show what reversing this costs us, and what acting on it would
gain.

Source: USDA ERR-358, 2024.
:::


## Food-insecure adults face higher disease prevalence {.scale-slide}

::: {.r-stretch}
![](figures/03_disease_burden.png){fig-align="center"}
:::

::: {.notes}
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 5: Disease Burden

Food insecurity is not just about hunger today. It is about disease tomorrow.

These are weighted prevalence rates from NHANES, the CDC's national
health survey, comparing food-insecure to food-secure adults. Obesity is
46.2% versus 40.7%. Hypertension is 40.3% versus 39.3%. Diabetes is 10.6%
versus 10.0%.

These differences may look modest, but applied across 35 million
food-insecure adults nationally, the obesity gap alone represents
roughly 1.9 million additional cases attributable to food insecurity.

The cost of those additional cases — to Medicare, Medicaid, and private
insurance — is $52.9 billion every year. That number is from Berkowitz et
al. (2018) in Health Affairs, the most rigorous economic analysis of
food insecurity's healthcare cost on record.

A note on methodology: the published literature on older NHANES cycles
reports larger disparities than what you see here. The 2017-2020 cycle
shows narrower differences. We're presenting our own analysis of the
most recent data rather than older quoted figures — methodological
honesty matters when the numbers go to Congress.

Source: NHANES 2017-March 2020; Berkowitz et al. (2018) Health Affairs.
:::


## Children with food assistance grow into healthier, more self-sufficient adults {.scale-slide}

::: {.r-stretch}
![](figures/04_lifetime_cost.png){fig-align="center"}
:::

::: {.notes}
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 6: Lifetime Cost

This is the children-to-adults slide. The most cited research on this
question is Hoynes, Schanzenbach and Almond (2016), American Economic Review.

They studied the rollout of the Food Stamp Program in the 1960s and 70s,
which expanded county by county over more than a decade. That gave them
a natural experiment: kids who got food assistance versus kids in
neighboring counties who didn't, all else roughly equal.

The kids who received food assistance, when followed into adulthood,
showed lower rates of metabolic syndrome (-27%), heart disease (-22%),
adult obesity (-21%), high blood pressure (-16%), and diabetes (-10%).
On the economic side, women who grew up with food assistance had +29%
higher economic self-sufficiency in adulthood, +6% higher earnings, and
-13% reliance on transfer programs.

The most recent extension of this work — Bailey, Hoynes, Rossin-Slater
and Walker (2020), using Social Security Administration earnings records
and 17 million people — finds a marginal value of public funds of 56-to-1.
For every $1 the federal government invested in early-childhood food
assistance, society got $56 of social benefit back in healthier adults,
higher earnings, lower disability claims, and longer lives.

Children who eat become functional adults. Children who don't, become
permanent costs. This is the strongest financial argument for early
nutrition investment that exists in the economics literature.

Source: Hoynes, Schanzenbach and Almond (AER 2016); Bailey et al. (NBER 2020).
:::


## 8 states acted. 42 are waiting. {.scale-slide}

::: {.r-stretch}
![](figures/05_universal_meals_evidence.png){fig-align="center"}
:::

::: {.notes}
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 7: The Fix

This is the call to action.

8 states have implemented universal free school meals as of the 2024-25
school year: California, Maine, Colorado, Minnesota, New Mexico,
Vermont, Massachusetts, and Michigan. Together they represent the
largest natural experiment in nutrition policy currently running in
the United States.

The measured outcomes from those states: school lunch participation
up 6%, an additional 233,656 daily meals served, household food
insecurity down 5.1% in families with children, childhood obesity down
0.6 percentage points in California's CEP schools, school suspensions
down 0.7 percentage points in Oregon.

These are real numbers from real states. The cost is approximately
$700 per child per year. The Berkowitz et al. healthcare-cost
research suggests every $1 invested in food security generates roughly
$2.60 in healthcare savings — and the Bailey et al. lifetime work
suggests $56 in total social return.

42 states have not yet acted. Federal action — universal free school
meals nationwide, restoration of the expanded Child Tax Credit,
permanent SNAP emergency allotments, full WIC funding — would extend
the proven results from these 8 states to the entire country.

The data is unambiguous. The evidence base is decades deep. The cost
per child is small. The lifetime return is enormous. This is not a
partisan question. It's an arithmetic one.

Thank you.

Source: FRAC State of Healthy School Meals for All (2024); California
Department of Education; Oregon Department of Education.
:::
